=Description=

"In July 2010, a group of international experts – amongst whom Nancy Neamtam, president and CEO of the Chantier de l’économie sociale – were mandated to prepare a training manual on the social and solidarity economy for a four-day course of the International Training Center of the International Labour Organisation (ILO) in Turin. The reader, entitled “The Reader 2010 Social and solidarity economy: building a common understanding”, offers an overview of the objectives and organisations of the social economy, as well as the challenges they face, and is now available online."
(http://www.fiess2011.org/en/681/)


Context:

"The social and solidarity economy is made up of collective approaches to sustainable development that contribute to building a world that is more fair and just. Within a global context, such an economy can only develop by establishing the link between economy and society, local and global, labour and investment, as well as production, consumption and the environment. An enabling public policy and programming framework is needed for the social economy to be able to develop and deliver to its fullest capacity. Then the social and solidarity economy can become an engine for development and play an increasingly important role in meeting the needs that are not adequately addressed by the public or private economy. The social and solidarity economy is one of the responses to the current economic crisis, both for the South and the North."
(http://www.fiess2011.org/en/)


